# TypeScript — Enums, Type Assertion, Classes & Interfaces

<details>
<summary>1️⃣ Enums</summary>

## What is an Enum?

An **enum** (short for enumeration) is a way to define a group of named constants. Think of it as a list of options — and TypeScript makes sure you only pick from that list.

Simple starting point:

```typescript
enum Color {
  Red,
  Green,
  Blue,
}

let myColor: Color = Color.Red;
console.log(myColor); // → 0
```

`Color` is the name of the enum — like a custom type that can only be `Red`, `Green`, or `Blue`. Nothing else.

By default, values start at `0` and increment — `Red = 0`, `Green = 1`, `Blue = 2`. You can also set them explicitly:

```typescript
enum Color {
  Red = 0,
  Green = 1,
  Blue = 2,
}
```

---

## Why use enums?

Compare these two versions:

```typescript
// ❌ without enum — string can be anything, typos go unnoticed
function turn(dir: string) {
  if (dir === 'Left') console.log('Turning left');
}

turn('left'); // ← no error, but wrong — 'left' !== 'Left'
```

```typescript
// ✅ with enum — TypeScript catches invalid values
enum Direction {
  Up,
  Down,
  Left,
  Right,
}

function turn(dir: Direction) {
  if (dir === Direction.Left) console.log('Turning left');
}

turn(Direction.Left); // ✅
turn('left'); // ❌ TypeScript error — not a valid Direction
```

<details>
<summary> 🧩 JS vs TS </summary>
## JavaScript vs TypeScript

```js
// JavaScript — no types, no safety
function add(a, b) {
  return a + b;
}

console.log(add(2, 3)); // → 5
console.log(add('2', 3)); // → "23" ← no error, but wrong!
```

```typescript
// TypeScript — types enforced
function add(a: number, b: number): number {
  return a + b;
}

console.log(add(2, 3)); // → 5
console.log(add('2', 3)); // ❌ Error — Argument of type 'string' is not assignable to parameter of type 'number'
```

> TypeScript catches the bug before the code even runs.

</details>

---

## String Enums

For readability, string enums are often preferred — easier to read in logs and the debugger:

```typescript
enum Status {
  Success = 'SUCCESS',
  Failure = 'FAILURE',
  Pending = 'PENDING',
}

function logStatus(status: Status) {
  console.log(`Current status: ${status}`);
}

logStatus(Status.Pending); // → "Current status: PENDING"
```

---

## Real-world example — UserRole

```typescript
enum UserRole {
  Guest = 'guest',
  User = 'user',
  Admin = 'admin',
}

function getWelcomeMessage(role: UserRole): string {
  if (role === UserRole.Admin) return 'Welcome, Admin!';
  if (role === UserRole.User) return 'Welcome back!';
  return 'Welcome, guest. Please log in.';
}

console.log(getWelcomeMessage(UserRole.Admin)); // → "Welcome, Admin!"
console.log(getWelcomeMessage(UserRole.Guest)); // → "Welcome, guest. Please log in."
```

---

## Summary

```
✅ Use enums when a variable should only take one of a fixed set of values
✅ Prefer string enums — easier to read in logs and debugger
✅ Enums prevent typos and invalid values at compile time
```

</details>

<details>
<summary>2️⃣ Type Assertion</summary>

## What is Type Assertion?

Sometimes TypeScript can't figure out what type a value is. **Type assertion** lets you tell the compiler: _"trust me, I know what this is."_

Simple starting point:

```typescript
let value: unknown = 'Hello!';

// without assertion — TypeScript doesn't know it's a string
console.log(value.toUpperCase()); // ❌ Error — 'value' is of type 'unknown'

// with assertion — we tell TypeScript it's a string
let result = value as string;
console.log(result.toUpperCase()); // ✅ → "HELLO!"
```

> It doesn't change the actual value — it only tells the compiler how to treat it.

---

## Basic syntax

There are two ways to assert a type. Always use `as` in `.tsx` files — angle brackets conflict with JSX:

```typescript
let value: unknown = 'Hello!';

// angle-bracket syntax — avoid in .tsx files
let result1 = <string>value;

// 'as' syntax — preferred, works everywhere
let result2 = value as string;
```

---

## Common use case — DOM elements

TypeScript knows `querySelector` can return many types of elements. If you know it's an input, assert it:

```typescript
const input = document.querySelector('input') as HTMLInputElement;
input.value = 'Alice'; // ✅ TypeScript now knows it's an input
```

Without assertion, TypeScript sees it as `Element | null` — no `.value` property.

---

## Common use case — API responses

TypeScript doesn't know the shape of parsed JSON. Assert it to get type safety:

```typescript
type Product = {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  price: number;
};

async function fetchProducts() {
  const response = await fetch('https://fakestoreapi.com/products');
  const products = (await response.json()) as Product[];

  products.forEach((product) => {
    console.log(`${product.title} — $${product.price}`);
  });
}
```

---

## Summary

```
✅ Use 'as' syntax — especially in .tsx files
✅ Assert types when TS can't infer them (DOM, JSON, unknown)
⚠️  Don't assert just to silence errors — only when you're confident about the type
```

</details>

<details>
<summary>3️⃣ Classes</summary>

## What is a class?

A **class** is a blueprint for creating objects. We already saw classes in JavaScript — TypeScript adds types and access control on top.

Simple starting point:

```typescript
class Person {
  name: string;
  age: number;

  constructor(name: string, age: number) {
    this.name = name;
    this.age = age;
  }

  greet(): void {
    console.log(`Hi, I'm ${this.name} and I'm ${this.age} years old.`);
  }
}

const alice = new Person('Alice', 25);
alice.greet(); // → "Hi, I'm Alice and I'm 25 years old."
```

`Person` is the blueprint. `alice` is an instance — a real object created from that blueprint.

---

## readonly and optional properties

```typescript
class Book {
  readonly title: string; // can't be changed after creation
  author?: string; // optional — may be undefined

  constructor(title: string, author?: string) {
    this.title = title;
    this.author = author;
  }
}

const book = new Book('The Hobbit', 'Tolkien');
book.title = 'Other'; // ❌ Error — title is readonly
```

---

## Access modifiers

TypeScript adds three access modifiers to control who can access a property:

```typescript
class BankAccount {
  private balance: number; // only accessible inside this class
  public owner: string; // accessible everywhere (default)

  constructor(owner: string, initialBalance: number) {
    this.owner = owner;
    this.balance = initialBalance;
  }

  getBalance(): number {
    return this.balance; // ✅ accessible inside the class
  }
}

const acc = new BankAccount('Alice', 1000);
console.log(acc.getBalance()); // ✅ → 1000
console.log(acc.balance); // ❌ Error — 'balance' is private
```

| Modifier    | Accessible from                 |
| ----------- | ------------------------------- |
| `public`    | Everywhere (default)            |
| `private`   | Only inside the class           |
| `protected` | Inside the class and subclasses |

---

## When to use classes

```
✅ You need to model an entity with both data and behaviour (User, BankAccount, Product)
✅ You need encapsulation — hiding internal details
✅ You need inheritance or shared logic across related objects

❌ You only need a shape/type → use type or interface instead
❌ You don't need methods or state → use a plain object
```

</details>

<details>
<summary>4️⃣ Inheritance & Abstract Classes</summary>

## Inheritance — extending a class

A class can **extend** another class to inherit its properties and methods.

Simple starting point:

```typescript
class Animal {
  name: string;

  constructor(name: string) {
    this.name = name;
  }

  speak(): void {
    console.log(`${this.name} makes a sound.`);
  }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
  speak(): void {
    console.log(`${this.name} barks!`); // overrides parent method
  }
}

const dog = new Dog('Rex');
dog.speak(); // → "Rex barks!"
```

`Dog` inherits `name` from `Animal` — no need to redefine it.

---

## super() — passing arguments to the parent

When a subclass has its own constructor, it must call `super()` first:

```typescript
class Dog extends Animal {
  breed: string;

  constructor(name: string, breed: string) {
    super(name); // ← passes 'name' up to Animal's constructor
    this.breed = breed;
  }

  speak(): void {
    console.log(`${this.name} the ${this.breed} barks!`);
  }
}

const dog = new Dog('Rex', 'Labrador');
dog.speak(); // → "Rex the Labrador barks!"
```

---

## Abstract classes

An **abstract class** is a base class that:

- **Cannot be instantiated directly** — you can't do `new Shape()`
- Can have **abstract methods** — no implementation, subclasses must provide it
- Can also have **concrete methods** — shared logic all subclasses get for free

Without abstract class, `describe()` gets copy-pasted into every subclass:

```typescript
// ❌ without abstract class — describe() duplicated everywhere
class Circle {
  describe(): void {
    console.log('I am a shape');
  } // duplicated
}
class Rectangle {
  describe(): void {
    console.log('I am a shape');
  } // duplicated
}
```

```typescript
// ✅ with abstract class — describe() lives once, getArea() is enforced
abstract class Shape {
  // abstract — every subclass MUST implement this
  abstract getArea(): number;

  // concrete — shared by all subclasses for free
  describe(): void {
    console.log(`This shape has an area of ${this.getArea()}`);
  }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
  constructor(public radius: number) {
    super();
  }

  getArea(): number {
    return Math.PI * this.radius * this.radius;
  }
}

class Rectangle extends Shape {
  constructor(
    public width: number,
    public height: number,
  ) {
    super();
  }

  getArea(): number {
    return this.width * this.height;
  }
}

const circle = new Circle(5);
circle.describe(); // → "This shape has an area of 78.53..."

const rect = new Rectangle(4, 6);
rect.describe(); // → "This shape has an area of 24"

// const shape = new Shape(); // ❌ Error — cannot instantiate abstract class
```

</details>

<details>
<summary>5️⃣ Interfaces vs Abstract Classes</summary>

## Interfaces — pure contracts

An **interface** defines the _shape_ of a class — what properties and methods it must have. No implementation, no logic.

Simple starting point:

```typescript
interface Greetable {
  name: string;
  greet(): void;
}

class Person implements Greetable {
  name: string;

  constructor(name: string) {
    this.name = name;
  }

  greet(): void {
    console.log(`Hi, I'm ${this.name}`);
  }
}

const alice = new Person('Alice');
alice.greet(); // → "Hi, I'm Alice"
```

`implements` means: _"this class promises to have everything the interface requires."_

---

## A class can implement multiple interfaces

```typescript
interface Drawable {
  draw(): void;
}

interface Resizable {
  resize(factor: number): void;
}

// one class, two contracts
class Circle implements Drawable, Resizable {
  draw(): void {
    console.log('Drawing a circle');
  }

  resize(factor: number): void {
    console.log(`Resizing by ${factor}`);
  }
}
```

---

## Interfaces vs Abstract Classes — side by side

```typescript
// Interface — contract only, no implementation
interface Flyable {
  fly(): void;
}

// Abstract Class — contract + shared logic
abstract class Vehicle {
  constructor(public name: string) {}

  abstract move(): void; // subclasses must implement

  describe(): void {
    console.log(`${this.name} is a vehicle.`); // shared — free for all subclasses
  }
}

// extends the abstract class AND implements the interface
class Plane extends Vehicle implements Flyable {
  move(): void {
    console.log(`${this.name} is moving on the runway.`);
  }

  fly(): void {
    console.log(`${this.name} is flying!`);
  }
}

const plane = new Plane('Boeing 747');
plane.describe(); // → "Boeing 747 is a vehicle."  (from abstract class)
plane.move(); // → "Boeing 747 is moving on the runway."
plane.fly(); // → "Boeing 747 is flying!"
```

---

## Key differences

| Feature               | Interface                      | Abstract Class                  |
| --------------------- | ------------------------------ | ------------------------------- |
| Implementation        | ❌ No                          | ✅ Yes (concrete methods)       |
| Constructors          | ❌ No                          | ✅ Yes                          |
| Multiple inheritance  | ✅ Yes (`implements` multiple) | ❌ No (single `extends`)        |
| Fields with modifiers | ❌ No                          | ✅ Yes (`private`, `protected`) |

---

## When to use which

```
Interface:
  ✅ Defining the shape of an object or API response
  ✅ Multiple inheritance needed
  ✅ No shared implementation needed

Abstract Class:
  ✅ Sharing logic across related classes
  ✅ Forcing subclasses to implement specific methods
  ✅ Need private/protected fields
```

> **Practical tip:** Default to interfaces. Reach for abstract classes only when you need shared implementation logic.

</details>

<details>
<summary>6️⃣ Quick Reference</summary>

### Enums

```typescript
enum Color {
  Red,
  Green,
  Blue,
} // numeric — Red=0, Green=1, Blue=2
enum Status {
  Active = 'active',
} // string — preferred for readability

let s: Status = Status.Active;
```

---

### Type Assertion

```typescript
// use 'as' — especially in .tsx files
const input = document.querySelector('input') as HTMLInputElement;
const data = (await response.json()) as MyType[];
```

---

### Class modifiers

```typescript
class Example {
  public name: string; // accessible everywhere (default)
  private secret: string; // only inside this class
  protected shared: string; // inside this class + subclasses
  readonly id: number; // can't be changed after construction
}
```

---

### Abstract class pattern

```typescript
abstract class Base {
  abstract doSomething(): void; // subclass must implement
  sharedMethod(): void { ... }  // free for all subclasses
}

class Concrete extends Base {
  doSomething(): void { ... } // required
}
```

---

### Interface pattern

```typescript
interface Greetable {
  name: string;
  greet(): void;
}

class Person implements Greetable {
  name = 'Alice';
  greet() {
    console.log(`Hi, I'm ${this.name}`);
  }
}
```

---

### Interface vs Abstract Class — one-liner

```
Interface    → "what it must have" (contract only)
Abstract     → "what it must have + what it already does" (contract + shared logic)
```

</details>
